context: In 1970, CBS Records revived <b0_0>the Embassy Records imprint<b0_0/> in UK and Europe, which had been defunct since CBS had taken control of Embassy's parent company, Oriole, in <b1_0>1964<b1_0/>. The purpose of the revived Embassy imprint was <b2_0>to release budget reissues of albums that had originally been released in the United States on Columbia Records<b2_0/> (or its subsidiaries). Many albums, by artists as diverse as Andy Williams, Johnny Cash, Barbra Streisand, the Byrds, Tammy Wynette, Laura Nyro and Sly & the Family Stone were issued on <b3_0><b4_0>Embassy<b4_0/><b3_0/>, before the label was once again discontinued in 1980.
